  <a href="#1" id="1">
   Releasing a heart attack victim from the hospital as soon as three days after their attack are becoming more common with new medical treatments.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   The early discharges are made possible with the introduction of tissue plasminogen activator, or TPA,
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   and balloon angioplasty. TPA, given right after a heart attack, can dissolve clots
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   while angioplasty can open up clogged arteries.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   Patients sent home early can return to work earlier that those kept longer,
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   while the number of medical problems suffered by both groups after six months were similar.
  </a>
  <a href="#7" id="7">
   The earlier release also has the benefit of significantly reducing medical costs.
  </a>
